rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: An ontology element is used as a property without having been explicitly declared as such using the primitives rdf:Property, owl:ObjectProperty or owl:DatatypeProperty. This pitfall is related with the common problems listed in [8].
The ontology lacks information about equivalent properties (owl:equivalentProperty) in the cases of duplicated relationships and/or attributes.

rdf:Description.oops:hasAffectedElement: There are elements following different naming conventions as for example: https://ontology.unifiedcyberontology.org/uco/marking/definitionType https://ontology.unifiedcyberontology.org/uco/observable/PIN
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology elements are not named following the same convention (for example CamelCase or use of delimiters as "-" or "_") . Some notions about naming conventions are provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Using different naming conventions in the ontology

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: An ontology element is used as a class without having been explicitly declared as such using the primitives owl:Class or rdfs:Class. This pitfall is related with the common problems listed in [8].

rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Missing domain or range in properties
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Object and/or datatype properties without domain or range (or none of them) are included in the ontology.

rdf:Description.oops:hasName: WARNING: the following classes do not have rdf:type owl:Class or equivalent.

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The contents of some annotation properties are swapped or misused. This pitfall might affect annotation properties related to natural language information (for example, annotations for naming such as rdfs:label or for providing descriptions such as rdfs:comment). Other types of annotation could also be affected as temporal, versioning information, among others.
Two or more classes have the same content for natural language annotations for naming, for example the rdfs:label annotation. This pitfall might involve lack of accuracy when defining terms.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Several classes with the same label

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall consists in creating an ontology element and failing to provide human readable annotations attached to it. Consequently, ontology elements lack annotation properties that label them (e.g. rdfs:label, lemon:LexicalEntry, skos:prefLabel or skos:altLabel) or that define them (e.g. rdfs:comment or dc:description). This pitfall is related to the guidelines provided in [5].
Ontology elements (classes, object properties and datatype properties) are created isolated, with no relation to the rest of the ontology.

This pitfall consists in missing the definition of equivalent classes (owl:equivalentClass) in case of duplicated concepts. When an ontology reuses terms from other ontologies, classes that have the same meaning should be defined as equivalent in order to benefit the interoperability between both ontologies.

This pitfall appears when any relationship (except for those that are defined as symmetric properties using owl:SymmetricProperty) does not have an inverse relationship (owl:inverseOf) defined within the ontology.
